rComments: I took the B03 course with Dr. Nestor a few years ago. That course was terrible (and there were reasons outside the prof's teaching for the difficulties). PSYD54 was much better. The Prof did a great job organizing the course. He's also very respectful and listens to your thoughts. I'd recommend taking PSYD54 with Adrian as it's a fair course.

Professor Nestor is a really great prof who cares about his students. Yes, the material in his lectures is difficult however, he provides you with all the tools necessary to do well in the course. If you don't understand something, he is more than willing to help if you're willing to put in the effort and learn.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Gives good feedback', 'Caring']

rComments: Great prof, I was a bit worried because of his computer course he taught. But in this course his assignments were reasonable and is generous with marking. Some lectures were more interesting than others, but they are well organized. There is no exams.

Matlab can be difficult especially when I never taken a programming course before. However, it looks really good when you want to go on to further psychology work, or research. Easy weekly assignments, difficult written midterm, very complicated final programming assignment.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lots of homework']

rComments: One of the greatest profs ive had at UTSC. EXTREMELY fair marker on critiques we have for the course and the final paper, as well as the presentation we have to do. I did much better than i thought i would have. If u have questions he is great in helping. No exam, 10% participation but u dont have to be there much. Just do the work, youll do fine

So I finally completed this course, and all i have to say afterdoing four months of prison time is that even though this course gets you to learn matlab, its mostly you learning it youself. If you want to learn it, try online because its not worth the stress this course will readily provide for you as gourmet dinner. Goodluck!

Just finished the course today. Was an absolute nightmare from start to finish. If you care about your GPA, I recommend you steer clear of this course. Even if you have a background in computers, it's still very challenging.   One of the more difficult courses you'll encounter at UTSC, and the professor doesn't make it any easier.
Skip class? You won't pass - this is actually true though, the class is pretty difficult, I'd suggest any other psychology course besides this and his advanced Matlab course.

He gives assignments that take like 5 days to do (really hard), the midterm was really challenging, and nothing is easy in this course. Highly recommend choosing wisely when selecting this course because the beginning starts off okay then it progresses to a very difficult level. I just pray I survive til the end.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Lots of homework', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: I took this course thinking it will be a breeze considering the name of the course 'Introduction to Computers in Psychology'.I would take out the 'introduction' part and replace it with 'Advance'. The professor is nice and helpful when you talk to him, but in terms of lectures, a lot is left ambiguous (assignments). Dont take it unless you have to!

Assignments are really hard, he doesn't speak clearly so it's hard to hear, midterm was a killer. Also, the course is called Intro to computers in psychology, but he teaches at a very advanced level. He gives impossible, unfair questions. Simply put, worst course at UTSC and the professor gets enjoyment out of making students suffer.

I was pretty skeptical before I took this course, but Professor Nestor is really intelligent and he is passionate about what he does. Even though it was his first time teaching the course he did a really good job, I wish he was teaching other courses as well. He is an extremely fair and understanding professor. Definitely recommend this course.
